me. I want Kellar to be in school like your regular kids, I don't want him to be treated any differently than your average kid, if I see that he is not on *par* w/other kids I will homeschool him though I don't plan on putting him in a public school he will go to a private christian school. I know some think that a special needs child will/could slow the rest of the class down, while I agree with this I have to ask what about the child that has no disabilities that is a disruption to the class? What about the kid that has parents that never work w/them at home and they come to school and still can't write their name in the 2nd grade and they are not learning as fast as the other students which in turn would put the class behind in some sense, should they be put in a special ed class in order to not slow down the others? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1139" language="en" documentId="4851" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="ChrisseeT" date="Last edited 12/02/2008" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a2854275/mainstreaming_special_needs_kids?cpg=2" topic="mainstreaming" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4851" notes="" title="Mainstreaming Special Needs Kids"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1139"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>